</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-01-24T02:25:55.964Z","body":"<p>This&nbsp;Australia Day, many of us will gather to reflect on and celebrate what’s great about our democracy.&nbsp;It’s our good fortune as a nation to be blessed with abundant natural resources that are our common wealth. Our fertile land, clean air and water underpin our country’s agricultural heritage, which has fed and clothed us.</p><p>Australia’s native wildlife is unique, and the bush where Australians walk, fish, hunt and camp is habitat for the animals that are emblems of the country itself. Traditional owners of the country have the longest continuing culture in the world, and a connection to the bush that goes back tens of thousands of years.</p><p>And then there’s the Australian character: tough, wry, tending to side with the underdog and not afraid of a fight to defend what matters to us. &nbsp;</p><p>In the battle that is gripping my community this coming&nbsp;Australia Day, my fifth generation farming family and I are siding with the underdogs against Big Coal. Or rather, they’re siding with us.&nbsp;The forest which bears our family name, our farm and our community are all&nbsp;under threat of devastation from open-cut coal mining.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-acbc538b-7721-4272-8cc3-002c8db6174e\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/23/1390517913054/89902f23-c39b-4052-bee9-2cc14718e0b7-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"The Namoi river. \" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The Namoi river. Photograph: maulescreek.org</figcaption> </figure> <p>Coal miner Whitehaven is <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/jan/13/protesters-lock-themselves-to-bulldozers-to-fight-coalmine-development\">rolling in the bulldozers</a> to clear thousands of hectares of the Leard State Forest at Maules Creek in northwest NSW. The company has <a href=\"http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/epbc/epbc_ap.pl?name=current_referral_detail&amp;proposal_id=5566\">approval</a> to build a new <a href=\"http://www.miningaustralia.com.au/news/activists-blockade-maules-creek-mine-site-as-prote\">13m tonne per year open cut coal mine</a>, the largest new mine in NSW.</p><p>Out here at Maules Creek, we face a <a href=\"http://www.theglobalmail.org/feature/the-coal-mine-and-maules-creek-ecological-haven-or-whitehaven/816/\">make-or-break fight</a> to defend the core things we value: our forest, land, water and air, our community, and our ability to farm the land. Having exhausted all official avenues, we are rising up as a community this Australia Day weekend and putting ourselves on the line to blockade the mine site.</p><p>The Maules Creek coal mine will drop the water table we depend on for our livelihood by five metres. It will dump thousands of tonnes of coal dust on surrounding farms each year. It has divided our once close community, and&nbsp;some environmentalists say the mine&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/site-archive/rural/news/content/201210/s3618613.htm\">will damage</a> the last remaining bushland left on the Liverpool Plains, a biodiversity hotspot&nbsp;with an&nbsp;important koala habitat. &nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-55e60abd-ac4c-44f5-89a6-aac6d1e69048\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/23/1390518081601/9a4624ef-93f1-44ae-a4f3-09fb4adccc30-460x276.png\" alt=\"5m drawdown was taken from the Namoi Water Study Map below. The dark blue is Maules Creek. Link\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Five meters drawdown taken from the Namoi Water.&nbsp;The dark blue is Maules Creek. <a href=\"http://www.namoicatchmentwaterstudy.com.au/client_images/1085533.pdf\">Source.</a></figcaption> </figure> <p>The scale of this mine is breathtaking. To put it in context, Griffith university&nbsp;professor Ian Lowe estimated that&nbsp;if the Maules Creek mine were a nation, the burning of the coal produced by the mine would <a href=\"http://www.maulescreek.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Appendix-4-Maules-Creek-Coal-Emissions.pdf\">rank 75th in the world</a> for total emissions, ahead of the greenhouse gas emissions of 140 entire countries.<br></p><p>Local farmers and environmentalists are working together in our opposition to the mine. We’re standing with Gomeroi traditional owners of the land, who are fighting to preserve and safeguard their heritage in the area.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.5;\">Whitehaven Coal and the NSW Minerals Council have been busy fighting those of us who have joined the </span><a href=\"http://www.echo.net.au/2014/01/leard-blockade-continues/\" style=\"font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.5;\">Leard blockade</a><span style=\"font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.5;\">, but they have known for years that we will fight this mine tooth and nail, and that we welcome any person from anywhere in this great country who will stand next to Maules Creek farmers to stop the mine. &nbsp;Over the last two weeks, as the Leard blockade has grown, we’ve supported traditional owners, and </span><a href=\"https://www.google.com.au/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;ved=0CCgQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fcommentisfree%2F2013%2Fdec%2F12%2Fan-open-letter-to-nsw-farmer-phil-laird-greenpeace-stands-by-you&amp;ei=faPhUv7uIKfYigeljYDABg&amp;usg=AFQjCNEsgmeU986YY5mBql00xnj0D0hcUA&amp;sig2=kkEpm4jiECEiHdiivCMIPg&amp;bvm=bv.59930103,d.aGc\" style=\"font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.5;\">environmentalists have supported us</a><span style=\"font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.5;\">. We’re all in this together.&nbsp;</span></p><p>All is not lost. There is an <a href=\"http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/mining-energy/maules-creek-in-breach/story-e6frg9df-1226798545521#\">unresolved question</a> as to whether Whitehaven made misleading statements about biodiversity offsets intended to protect threatened species in order to gain approval for the mine. There is also a request pending <a href=\"http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/minister-failed-to-act-on-maules-creek-mine-stopwork-order-20140117-30yep.html\">for a protection order</a> for Aboriginal cultural heritage sites that have been damaged.</p><p>The federal government has questions to answer from traditional owners and environmentalists, and has been asked to stop work while investigations are underway.&nbsp;How is it that the devastating land clearing for this mine can begin when these issues are not settled?&nbsp;Why is the construction work still underway?<br></p><p>Environment minister Greg Hunt has the power to revoke Whitehaven’s approval and end the conflict that is dividing our community.&nbsp;We see it as our duty to protect our irreplaceable natural assets, our land and future generations from this destructive mine.&nbsp;At our blockade on Australia Day, we’ll be proud, united Australians, fighting like our forebears for what really matters.</p>","headline":"This Australia day, us underdogs will fight Big Coal to save Maules Creek","trailText":"<b>Phil Laird:&nbsp;</b>In the battle that is gripping my community, my fifth generation farming family and I are siding with traditional owners and environmentalists&nbsp;against miners&nbsp;to save the land we love","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m64v","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/23/1390517810090/cfbd0ad1-dee6-4923-be6a-376220f3bdaf-140x84.png","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/23/1390517810090/cfbd0ad1-dee6-4923-be6a-376220f3bdaf-140x84.png","wordcount":"1","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"427893675","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"52e19a40e4b065f7ddbb83fd","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Phil Laird