cessors – been passing crime-related legislation at the rate of <a href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga?page=6\" title=\"\">approximately one act a year</a>, duly claimed credit and possibly sighed with relief, given the big cuts in spending on law and order. But even a glance at the trend behind the headlines suggests crime and policing policy has less influence on the figures than politicians want to believe. Crime has been falling since 1995, and looks set to carry on falling, whether counted by the Office for National Statistics' crime survey, or the police records that the ONS says it can no longer authenticate in the wake of evidence suggesting what the chief inspector of constabulary, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/dec/18/police-crime-figures-manipulation-chief-inspector\" title=\"\">Tom Winsor, politely called manipulation</a>.</p><p>But if not government policy, then what, criminologists and <a href=\"http://www.ukjusticepolicyreview.org.uk/what-we-ve-been-up-to\" title=\"\">justice specialists</a> wonder? The detail contains some of the answers: crimes such as vandalism, burglary and car theft, which once made up a large part of total crime, have fallen steeply – due to better-designed and lit public areas and more sophisticated security. Harder to grapple with is the rise within the overall figures of some types of crime. Shoplifting – which might be exacerbated by austerity – is up slightly overall, but has risen significantly in regions such as the West Midlands and Merseyside. Cause, or mere correlation? Reported domestic violence, which appears more prevalent when times are hard, is rising. But – like historic sex abuse – it is also a crime to which police forces are more sensitive than they were.</p><p>Many would say it's prison, stupid. Rising prison populations track falling crime numbers. Maybe. But it's a pricey option. More and more evidence – from Norway <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/04/alternatives-incarceration-prison-numbers\" title=\"\">to New York</a> – shows ideas like restorative justice and drug treatment do it better – and cheaper.</p>","headline":"Crime figures: number crunching","trailText":"<strong>Editorial:</strong> The trend behind the headlines suggests crime and policing policy has less influence than politicians want to believe","newspaperPageNumber":"32","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m64h","wordcount":"462","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"427896503","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8591957","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Editorial","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-24T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2031848","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-27T00:10:46Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/24/crime-figures-policing-policy-editorial","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/24/crime-figures-policing-policy-editorial","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","webTitle":"Comment is free","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","references":[]},{"id":"society/society","webTitle":"Society","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/society","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/society/society","references":[]},{"id":"society/prisons-and-probation","webTitle":"Prisons and probation","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/prisons-and-probation","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/society/prisons-and-probation","references":[]},{"id":"