elp to make life difficult for the generals in other ways, too. The public's mood coincides with a long period of public spending cuts. The Treasury sniffs the doubting political breeze, and therefore sees the chance to make savings in a department with a relatively large budget – <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/221885/budget2013_complete.pdf\" title=\"\">£40bn this year</a> – and relatively little prospect of new large spending. On Thursday <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/news/final-tranche-of-armed-forces-redundancies\" title=\"\"> the defence secretary announced</a> another 1,505 armed forces redundancies, mainly in the army, the fourth such announcement since the coalition took office. For all that, few would bet against further cuts after the general election.</p><p>But it won't do for the politicians and service chiefs simply to blame the public for the fact that they must operate in reduced circumstances. A significant part of the problem the MoD faces is of its own devising. It is not the public that has decided to press ahead with the Trident nuclear weapons replacement programme – <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/research/briefing-papers/SN06526/update-on-the-trident-successor-programme\" title=\"\">official cost £15-20bn</a>. Nor is it the voters who are responsible for the fact that the UK is building two new aircraft carriers – <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/nov/04/aircraft-carriers-cost-6bn\" title=\"\">official cost currently £6.2bn</a>. These are choices made at the top, and they inevitably constrain other defence spending options. Add in the ministry's unenviable but justified reputation for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/jan/14/ministry-of-defence-failed-computer-system\" title=\"\">wasteful spending</a> and there can be little dispute that the MoD is the author of its own fate, whether for good or ill. If the public shares some responsibility for these questionable priorities, that is ascribable to the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/16/leader-comment-military-options-sense-about-defence\" title=\"\">lack of serious political debate</a> about UK defence options rather than to anything else.</p><p>One of the threads that winds through this unsatisfactory story is Britain's often blundering response to the genuine external and internal security challenge posed to this country, among others, by the 9/11 and other terror attacks. But it was not just the military response that miscued. It was the domestic security response, too. On Thursday a report by the parliamentary <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/joint-select/human-rights-committee/news/tpims-substantive/\" title=\"\">joint committee on human rights</a> found some of the toughest counter-terrorism powers (<a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24803069\" title=\"\">known as TPim orders</a>) are simply \"withering on the vine\". It questioned whether the powers are of the practical use claimed by government. The committee rightly calls for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jan/23/uk-counter-terrorism-powers-review-watchdog\" title=\"\">a thorough re-examination and review</a> of all such powers after the election.</p><p>There is a resonantly important common theme here. In both cases, military and security, the response to 9/11 and jihadist terrorism has been massive and expensive. In both cases it has been of debatable effectiveness. In some respects, but not all, the policies have been counter-productive, feeding the radicalism not starving it. To say that is not, in any way, to dismiss the seriousness of the threat or the need for effective responses. It is, though, to question the effectiveness of what has been done, whether in the mountains of Afghanistan or the streets of British cities. We will continue to need effective defences to protect our people and deter our enemies, just as we will need effective anti-terror laws for the same reason. In both cases, the need is for strategies that work better than the current ones have done – and for a calmer and more objective debate about what these should be. Hopefully, that is beginning to be possible.</p>","headline":"Anti-terrorism strategies: the case for thinking differently","trailText":"<strong>Editorial:</strong> The response to 9/11 and jihadist terrorism has been massive, expensive and of debatable effectiveness","newspaperPageNumber":"32","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m64g","wordcount":"686","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"427896352","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8591963","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Editorial","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-24T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2031847","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-26T23:55:28Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/23/anti-terrorism-strategies-editorial","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/23/anti-terrorism-strategies-editorial","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","webTitle":"Comment is free","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","references":[]},{"id":"uk/uksecurity","webTitle":"UK security and counter-terrorism","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/uksecurity","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/uk/uksecurity","references":[]},{"id":"uk/uk","webTitle":"UK news","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/